post_text: Even through virtual learning the Kindergarten students of Zapata North Elementary were able to experience our Annual Gingerbread Man search. All of the ZNES Kindergarten students received a Gingerbread packet which included a virtual school t-shirt, a cowboy hat, and a gingerbread cookie in a box from Los Pasteles bakery which they were able to decorate on their own at home. This is the 30th year of the Gingerbread Man search. May the tradition continue for many years to come! ZNES Kinder teachers, Mrs. Frances Garcia, Mrs. Frances Campos, Ms. America De La Cruz, and Ms. Vianey Caballero would like to thank all those who participated in this activity!! A huge thanks goes out to: Esther Gavilanes & Los Pasteles Bakery, ZCISD Superintendent Carlos Gonzalez, Zapata County Fire Department staff Chief Meza, Nina Meza, Hugo Rodriguez, IBC Bank President Ricardo Ramirez, Zapata County District Clerk Dora Casta√±on, parents, and ZNES staff.

Parents of enrolled students will be asked to make a commitment for their child(ren) to choose either in-person, hybrid or full 100% remote at-home learning for the entire fall semester. In order for Zapata County ISD to finalize staffing requirements. The deadline for this form has been extended.

Your child‚Äôs schedule and teacher assignments cannot be finalized until we receive your commitment, so we greatly appreciate your considering completing the form as soon as possible.

Each learning model requires daily progress monitoring. In the event of a county or state shutdown order, all students will be transferred to the 100% Remote At-Home Learning Model.

post_text: Thank you Zapata Middle School Principal, Mrs. M. Guerra & Teacher Mrs. Olga Guzman for partnering with Communities In Schools in participating with the National Do The Write Thing essay initiative. Winners for Zapata Middle School are Angel Sarmiento & Anner Gonzalez. Top Female National Ambassador was Anner Gonzalez. She won amongst all CIS middle schools in Laredo & Hebbronville. Her essay will be published and archived in the Library of Congress in Washington DC. We are so proud of you, Anner Gonzalez.

post_text:
2020 Census!!

The Census Bureau will deliver 2020 Census invitations and paper questionnaires at the front doors of roughly 5.1 million stateside households including: Bandera, Dimmit, Edwards, Frio, Jim Hogg, Kinney, La Salle, Maverick, Medina, Real, Webb, Zapata, Zavala. This operation is crucial to ensure a complete and accurate count of all communities, which helps guide hundreds of billions of dollars in public and private sector spending per year.

People are strongly encouraged to respond promptly to the 2020 Census using the ID number included in the questionnaire packet. Responding with a census ID or the paper questionnaire helps ensure the best count of their community. People can respond online, by phone or by using the paper form in the packet.

For more information, please visit the 2020 Census COVID-19 operational adjustments page.

post_text: Villarreal Elementary administrators, teachers and staff would like to thank Zapata County Officials, Zapata County Sheriff's Office, ZCISD Administrators, ZCISD Transportation Department, and ZCISD Police Department for supporting and assisting in our small parade. The parade was for Villarreal Elementary families and students to show them that V.E.S. staff supports and cares about students during this difficult time. A special thank you to V.E.S. teachers and staff for making this event extra special. To the parents and students, thank you for following guidelines provided by the district and county officials by staying and watching from home or staying in your vehicles with your families and wearing masks. Again, thanks to all for making this event a success! Villarreal Elementary appreciates all your support .

post_text: The pandemic we are currently facing has pushed switching from face-to-face classes, traditional classes, to what is now considered satellite classrooms, or online classes. Fortunately, with the technology at our fingertips it has made connecting to our students, our future, easier than what could have been. Administrators, teachers, and students at ZNES have really brought to light the lengths we go to ensure our students know how much we care for and miss them. Staff meetings, team meetings and student meetings have been somewhat forced to embrace this budding technology. Faced with these trials and tribulations, we have supported and leaned on each other to ensure success.

The Career Technical Education Department and the Agriculture Science department under the direction of Fernando Rodriguez and Joevanna Sanchez put on an educational farm day at the request of PreK teachers who were teaching a unit related to the topic. All ZCISD preK students had the opportunity to rotate among 6 stations directed by FFA students who taught them facts about care, feeding, and handling animals. Group Photos were taken by student photographers from the commercial photography class under Robert Perez and cookies were provided by the culinary arts class under direction of Imelda Flores.
Congratulations to all involved in this event and much appreciation to those individuals who loaned their farm/show animals for this event.

In this week‚Äôs Character Ed lesson, students at Zapata South Elementary learned the importance of EMPATHY and the effect it can make in our society. Students watched a video about Eden‚Äôs journey at Saint Jude which was tied in to our Pennies for Patients campaign, highlighting the importance of helping those in need. Students then watched a short animated film ‚ÄúDear Basketball,‚Äù by the late Kobe Bryant which focused on PASSION (drive/motivation/perseverance). Through these videos and discussions, students were inspired to display good sportsmanship, responsibility, team work, empathy, and healthy habits that will shape them into well-rounded individuals. ‚ù§Ô∏è ZSES is proud to say that we have AMAZING kids with GREAT CHARACTER!

post_text: On Monday, March 2, 2020, ZNES students paid homage to the late, great Dr. Seuss, Theodor Seuss Geisel. The students wore shirts depicting different characters found in his many books as well as made "Green Eggs and Ham". Local dignitaries, officers, royalty and students were invited to read to the students. In the words of the great Dr. Seuss, "The more that you read, the more things you will know. The more that you learn, the more places you'll go."

post_text: Texas A&M AgriLife Healthy South Texas and Zapata Co. ISD invited students to attend the ‚ÄúPath to the Plate Youth Expo.‚Äù Zapata High School students, that serve as Youth Ambassadors for the program, presented to students on a rotation basis. The Expo‚Äôs goal was to correct misinformation about the production of our food supply and its effect on human health. This event was like a traditional agricultural literacy day; however, it was specific to the connection between agriculture and health. This event will keep us on track to becoming ‚ÄúHealthy South Texas Recognized Schools!‚Äù
text: Texas A&M AgriLife Healthy South Texas and Zapata Co. ISD invited students to attend the ‚ÄúPath to the Plate Youth Expo.‚Äù Zapata High School students, that serve as Youth Ambassadors for the program, presented to students on a rotation basis. The Expo‚Äôs goal was to correct misinformation about the production of our food supply and its effect on human health. This event will keep us on track to becoming ‚ÄúHealthy South Texas Recognized Schools!‚Äù

post_text: Villarreal Elementary had their annual Pennies for Patients Kickoff Assembly. V.E.S. accepted the challenge to help find a cure for leukemia and lymphoma by participating in this special fundraiser. Jojo Guevara and Julie Duran were our Honored Heroes honored at this assembly. V.E.S. has been helping for this great cause every year. This challenge will last approximately a month. Administrators, teachers, staff and students would like to invite parents and the community to help by donating money. V.E.S. would like to thank Ms. Frida Alfaro, Pennies for Patients representative for a great and very informative presentation.

post_text:
IRS Certifies ZHS students as Tax Preparers

Zapata High School Students were trained by an IRS agent this past semester to become tax preparer volunteers through the Volunteer Income Tax Assistance (VITA) program. This is a new initiative that began this year with the enthusiastic support and guidance of ZHS Career Technical Education (CTE) teacher, Mrs. Celina Canales. The students and teacher attended an intensive training by the IRS division and took an exam to become certified tax preparers. They are inviting the public to take advantage of the new free service offered on Mondays and Wednesdays beginning Jan. 27, 2020 from 4:30-6:30 pm. Location will be at Zapata High School. You may get more information by visiting www.zcisd.org under latest news.
From L-r: Aracely Barrientos, Jessica Barrera, Alexandra Rodriguez, and Jose Alvarado.

IRS-certified Career Technical Education (CTE) student and teacher volunteers from the newly formed Zapata ISD VITA program will provide FREE basic income tax preparation. Career Technical Education Students from Zapata High School were trained by IRS to become IRS-certified income tax preparers and will offer FREE tax services to individuals that make $66,000 or less, to individuals with disabilities, to the elderly and do limited English speaking taxpayers who need assistance in preparing their own tax returns.
The Zapata HS VITA program is under the direction of the ZCISD CTE Department: Mrs. Janie Rodriguez, Career and College Readiness Director and Mrs. Celina Canales, ZHS Site Coordinator. For more information, call 956-750-3730
